  "prompt": "Which one is better: the American Dream or the American dream? Dream with a capital letter or not?",
  "response": "The difference between \"the American Dream\" with a capital \"D\" and \"the American dream\" with a lowercase \"d\" typically depends on the context in which you're using the phrase.\n\n\"The American Dream\" (with a capital \"D\") usually refers to the specific cultural and historical concept in the United States that embodies ideals such as freedom, opportunity, and success through hard work. It implies a recognized and defined set of beliefs and aspirations.\n\nOn the other hand, \"the American dream\" (with a lowercase \"d\") can be used more generally to refer to similar aspirations without necessarily invoking the same historical and cultural significance.\n\nSo, if you're discussing the established concept, \"the American Dream\" would be more appropriate. If you're using it in a broader sense, then \"the American dream\" could work.",
